Coronaviruses such as human coronavirus 229E (HCoV 229E) and HCoV OC43 are responsible for variants of the common cold, while SARS-CoV caused the outbreak of severe acute respiratory syndrome in 2003, which killed more than 800 people (
1
). The human coronavirus NL63, first described in March 2004, has been identified as the causative agent of respiratory disease in very young children and in immunocompromised adults (2). Furthermore, HCoV-NL63 infection has been associated with laryngotracheitis (croup) (3) and Kawasaki disease, although the latter has been contested by a recent study (4).
